{
  "answer": "**In the *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, the eight forms of marriage (*vivāha*) are defined in Chapter 1 (\"Chapter on Conduct\"), section 3 (\"Marriage\"), specifically in verses 58–61.**[^1][^2][^3][^4]\n\nThese are:\n- **Brāhma**: A maiden, adorned according to one's ability, is given away after being invited (a son from this purifies 21 generations on both sides). // Yj_1.58 //\n- **Daiva**: She is given to a priest during a sacrifice (purifies 14 generations); **Ārṣa**: By giving a pair of cattle (purifies 6 generations). // Yj_1.59 //\n- **Prajāpatya** (here called *Kāya*): She is given to a suitor with the words, \"Practice *dharma* together\" (purifies 6 ancestors on each side, plus himself). // Yj_1.60 //\n- **Āsura**: By giving wealth; **Gāndharva**: By mutual agreement; **Rākṣasa**: By capturing her in battle; **Paiśāca**: By deceitfully seducing a maiden. // Yj_1.61 //\n\nThis matches the traditional eightfold classification found in other Dharmaśāstras (e.g., *Manusmṛti* 3.20–44), though the text here emphasizes the purifying power of sons from the approved forms (the first four). The corpus does not contain explicit prior mentions of \"eight forms,\" but these verses systematically define them.\n\n[^1]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [p-4ad3d1](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-4ad3d1).\n[^2]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [p-987352](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-987352).\n[^3]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [p-ee4dce](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-ee4dce).\n[^4]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [p-f1f83f](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-f1f83f).",
